# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: consumer-electronics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] The most common 2G technology has been the GSM standard, which became the first globally adopted framework for mobile communications.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Other 2G technologies include cdmaOne and the now-discontinued Digital AMPS (D-AMPS/TDMA), as well as the Personal Digital Cellular (PDC) and Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) in Japan.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] The transition to digital technology enabled the implementation of encryption for voice calls and data transmission, significantly improving the security of mobile communications while also increasing capacity and efficiency compared to earlier analog systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2G networks were primarily designed to support voice calls and Short Message Service (SMS), with later advancements such as General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) enabling always-on packet data services, including email and limited internet access.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2G was succeeded by 3G technology, which provided higher data transfer rates and expanded mobile internet capabilities.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] In 1990, AT&T Bell Labs engineers Jesse Russell, Farhad Barzegar and Can A.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Eryaman filed a patent for a digital mobile phone that supports the transmission of digital data.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Their patent was cited several years later by Nokia and Motorola when they were developing 2G digital mobile phones.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2G was first commercially launched in 1991 by Radiolinja (now part of Elisa Oyj) in Finland in the form of GSM, which was defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] The Telecommunications Industry Association (TIA) defined the cdmaOne (IS-95) 2G standard, with an eight to tenfold increase in voice call capacity compared to analog AMPS.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] The first deployment of cdmaOne was in 1995.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] In North America, Digital AMPS (IS-54 and IS-136) and cdmaOne (IS-95) were dominant, but GSM was also used.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Later 2G releases in the GSM space, often referred to as 2.5G and 2.75G, include General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) and Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] GPRS allows 2G networks to achieve a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 40 kbit/s (5 kB/s).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] EDGE increases this capacity, providing a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 384 kbit/s (48 kB/s).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2.5G ("second-and-a-half generation") refers to 2G systems that incorporate a packet-switched domain alongside the existing circuit-switched domain, most commonly implemented through General Packet Radio Service (GPRS).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] GPRS enables packet-based data transmission by dynamically allocating multiple timeslots to users, improving network efficiency.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] However, this does not inherently provide higher speeds, as similar techniques, such as timeslot bundling, are also employed in circuit-switched data services like High-Speed Circuit-Switched Data (HSCSD).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Within GPRS-enabled 2G systems, the theoretical maximum transfer rate is 40 kbit/s (5 kB/s).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2.75G refers to the evolution of GPRS networks into EDGE (Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution) networks, achieved through the introduction of 8PSK (8 Phase Shift Keying) encoding.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] While the symbol rate remained constant at 270.833 samples per second, the use of 8PSK allowed each symbol to carry three bits instead of one, significantly increasing data transmission efficiency.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE), also known as Enhanced GPRS (EGPRS) or IMT Single Carrier (IMT-SC), is a backward-compatible digital mobile phone technology built as an extension to standard GSM.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] First deployed in 2003 by AT&T in the United States, EDGE offers a theoretical maximum transfer speed of 384 kbit/s (48 kB/s).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Evolved EDGE (also known as EDGE Evolution or 2.875G) is an enhancement of the EDGE mobile technology that was introduced as a late-stage upgrade to 2G networks.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] While EDGE was first deployed in the early 2000s as part of GSM networks, Evolved EDGE was launched much later, coinciding with the widespread adoption of 3G technologies such as HSPA and just before the emergence of 4G networks.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] This timing limited its practical application.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Evolved EDGE increased data throughput and reduced latencies (down to 80 ms) by utilizing improved modulation techniques, dual carrier support, dual antennas, and turbo codes.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] It achieved peak data rates of up to 1 Mbit/s, significantly enhancing network efficiency for operators that had not yet transitioned to 3G or 4G infrastructures.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] However, despite its technical improvements, Evolved EDGE was never widely deployed.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] By the time it became available, most network operators were focused on implementing more advanced technologies like UMTS and LTE.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] As of 2016, no commercial networks were reported to support Evolved EDGE.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] 2G, understood as GSM and CdmaOne, has been superseded by newer technologies such as 3G (UMTS / CDMA2000), 4G (LTE / WiMAX) and 5G (5G NR).
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] However, 2G networks were still available as of 2023 in most parts of the world, while notably excluding the majority of carriers in North America, East Asia, and Australia.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Many modern LTE-enabled devices have the ability to fall back to 2G for phone calls, necessary especially in rural areas where later generations have not yet been implemented.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] In some places, its successor 3G is being shut down rather than 2G – Vodafone previously announced that it had switched off 3G across Europe in 2020 but still retains 2G as a fallback service.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] In the US T-Mobile shut down their 3G services while retaining their 2G GSM network.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Various carriers have made announcements that 2G technology in the United States, Japan, Australia, and other countries are in the process of being shut down, or have already shut down 2G services so that carriers can re-use the frequencies for newer technologies (e.g.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] As a legacy protocol, 2G connectivity is considered insecure.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Specifically, there exist well known methods to attack weaknesses in GSM since 2009 with practical use in crime.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Attack routes on 2G CdmaOne were found later and remain less publicized.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Android 12 and later provide a network setting to disable 2G connectivity for the device. iOS 16 and later can disable 2G connectivity by enabling Lockdown Mode.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] In some parts of the world, including the United Kingdom, 2G remains widely used for older feature phones and for internet of things (IoT) devices such as smart meters, eCall systems and vehicle trackers to avoid the high patent licensing cost of newer technologies.
[src:consumer-electronics/2g] Terminating 2G services could leave vulnerable people who rely on 2G infrastructure unable to communicate even with emergency contacts, causing harm and possibly deaths.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:consumer-electronics/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed by a team led by French computer scientist Jean Ichbiah of Honeywell under contract to the United States Department of Defense (DoD) from 1977 to 1983 to supersede over 450 programming languages then used by the DoD.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada was named after Ada Lovelace (1815–1852), who has been credited as the first computer programmer.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed for embedded and real-time systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Tucker Taft of Intermetrics between 1992 and 1995, improved support for systems, numerical, financial, and object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Features of Ada include strong typing, modular programming mechanisms (packages), run-time checking, parallel processing (tasks, synchronous message passing, protected objects, and nondeterministic select statements), exception handling, and generics.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 added support for object-oriented programming, including dynamic dispatch.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The syntax of Ada minimizes choices of ways to perform basic operations, and prefers English keywords (such as `or else` and `and then`) to symbols (such as `||` and `&&`).
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada uses the basic arithmetical operators `+`, `-`, `*`, and `/`, but avoids using other symbols.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Code blocks are delimited by words such as 'declare', 'begin', and 'end', where the 'end' (in most cases) is followed by the keyword of the block that it closes (e.g., `if` ...
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In the case of conditional blocks this avoids a *dangling else* that could pair with the wrong nested 'if'-expression in other languages such as C or Java.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada is designed for developing very large software systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada packages can be compiled separately.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada package specifications (the package interface) can also be compiled separately without the implementation to check for consistency.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This makes it possible to detect problems early during the design phase, before implementation starts.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] A large number of compile-time checks are supported to help avoid bugs that would not be detectable until run time in some other languages or would require explicit checks to be added to the source code.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] For example, the syntax requires explicitly named closing of blocks to prevent errors due to mismatched end tokens.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The adherence to strong typing allows detecting many common software errors (wrong parameters, range violations, invalid references, mismatched types, etc.) either during compile time, or otherwise during run time.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] As concurrency is part of the language specification, the compiler can in some cases detect potential deadlocks.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Compilers also commonly check for misspelled identifiers, visibility of packages, redundant declarations, etc. and can provide warnings and useful suggestions on how to fix the error.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada also supports run-time checks to protect against access to unallocated memory, buffer overflow errors, range violations, off-by-one errors, array access errors, and other detectable bugs.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] These checks can be disabled in the interest of runtime efficiency, but can often be compiled efficiently.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] It also includes facilities to help program verification.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] For these reasons, Ada is sometimes used in critical systems, where any anomaly might lead to very serious consequences, e.g., accidental death, injury or severe financial loss.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Examples of systems where Ada is used include avionics, air traffic control, railways, banking, military and space technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada's dynamic memory management is high-level and type-safe.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada has no generic or untyped pointers, nor does it implicitly declare any pointer type.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Instead, all dynamic memory allocation and deallocation must occur via explicitly declared *access types*.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Each access type has an associated *storage pool* that handles the low-level details of memory management; the programmer can either use the default storage pool or define new ones (this is particularly relevant for non-uniform memory access).
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] It is even possible to declare several different access types that all designate the same type but use different storage pools.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Also, the language provides for *accessibility checks*, both at compile time and at run time, that ensures that an *access value* cannot outlive the type of the object it points to.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Though the semantics of the language allow automatic garbage collection of inaccessible objects, most implementations do not support it by default, as it would cause unpredictable behaviour in real-time systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada supports a limited form of region-based memory management, and in Ada, destroying a storage pool also destroys all the objects in the pool.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] A double dash (`--`), resembling an em dash, denotes comment text.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Comments stop at end of line; there is intentionally no way to make a comment span multiple lines, to prevent unclosed comments from accidentally voiding whole sections of source code.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Disabling a whole block of code therefore requires the prefixing of each line (or column) individually with `--`.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] While this clearly denotes disabled code by creating a column of repeated '--' down the page, it also renders the experimental dis/re-enablement of large blocks a more drawn-out process in editors without block commenting support.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The semicolon (`;`) is a statement terminator, and the null or no-operation statement is `null;`.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] A single `;` without a statement to terminate is not allowed.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Unlike most ISO standards, the Ada language definition (known as the *Ada Reference Manual* or *ARM*, or sometimes the *Language Reference Manual* or *LRM*) is free content.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Thus, it is a common reference for Ada programmers, not only programmers implementing Ada compilers.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Apart from the reference manual, there is also an extensive rationale document which explains the language design and the use of various language constructs.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This document is also widely used by programmers.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] When the language was revised, a new rationale document was written.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] One notable free software tool that is used by many Ada programmers to aid them in writing Ada source code is the GNAT Programming Studio, and GNAT which is part of the GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In the 1970s the US Department of Defense (DoD) became concerned by the number of different programming languages being used for its embedded computer system projects, many of which were obsolete or hardware-dependent, and none of which supported safe modular programming.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In 1975, a working group, the High Order Language Working Group (HOLWG), was formed with the intent to reduce this number by finding or creating a programming language generally suitable for the department's and the UK Ministry of Defence's requirements.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] After many iterations beginning with an original straw-man proposal the eventual programming language was named Ada.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The total number of high-level programming languages in use for such projects fell from over 450 in 1983 to 37 by 1996.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] HOLWG crafted the **Steelman language requirements**, a series of documents stating the requirements they felt a programming language should satisfy.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Many existing languages were formally reviewed, but the team concluded in 1977 that no existing language met the specifications.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The requirements were created by the United States Department of Defense in *The Department of Defense Common High Order Language program* in 1978.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The predecessors of this document were called, in order, "Strawman", "Woodenman", "Tinman" and "Ironman".
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The requirements focused on the needs of embedded computer applications, and emphasised reliability, maintainability, and efficiency.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Notably, they included exception handling facilities, run-time checking, and parallel computing.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] It was concluded that no existing language met these criteria to a sufficient extent, so a contest was called to create a language that would be closer to fulfilling them.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The design that won this contest became the Ada programming language.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The resulting language followed the Steelman requirements closely, though not exactly.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In April 1978, after public scrutiny, the Red and Green proposals passed to the next phase.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In May 1979, the Green proposal, designed by Jean Ichbiah at Honeywell, was chosen and given the name Ada—after Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace, usually known as Ada Lovelace.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This proposal was influenced by the language LIS that Ichbiah and his group had developed in the 1970s.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The preliminary Ada reference manual was published in ACM SIGPLAN Notices in June 1979.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Military Standard reference manual was approved on December 10, 1980 (Ada Lovelace's birthday), and given the number MIL-STD-1815 in honor of Ada Lovelace's birth year.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In 1981, Tony Hoare took advantage of his Turing Award speech to criticize Ada for being overly complex and hence unreliable, but subsequently seemed to recant in the foreword he wrote for an Ada textbook.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada attracted much attention from the programming community as a whole during its early days.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Its backers and others predicted that it might become a dominant language for general purpose programming and not only defense-related work.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ichbiah publicly stated that within ten years, only two programming languages would remain: Ada and Lisp.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Early Ada compilers struggled to implement the large, complex language, and both compile-time and run-time performance tended to be slow and tools primitive.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Compiler vendors expended most of their efforts in passing the massive, language-conformance-testing, government-required Ada Compiler Validation Capability (ACVC) validation suite that was required in another novel feature of the Ada language effort.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The first validated Ada implementation was the NYU Ada/Ed translator, certified on April 11, 1983.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] NYU Ada/Ed is implemented in the high-level set language SETL.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Several commercial companies began offering Ada compilers and associated development tools, including Alsys, TeleSoft, DDC-I, Advanced Computer Techniques, Tartan Laboratories, Irvine Compiler, TLD Systems, and Verdix.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] In 1991, the US Department of Defense began to require the use of Ada (the *Ada mandate*) for all software, though exceptions to this rule were often granted.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Department of Defense Ada mandate was effectively removed in 1997, as the DoD began to embrace commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Similar requirements existed in other NATO countries: Ada was required for NATO systems involving command and control and other functions, and Ada was the mandated or preferred language for defense-related applications in countries such as Sweden, Germany, and Canada.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] By the late 1980s and early 1990s, Ada compilers had improved in performance, but there were still barriers to fully exploiting Ada's abilities, including a tasking model that was different from what most real-time programmers were used to.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Canadian Automated Air Traffic System was written in 1 million lines of Ada (SLOC count).
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] It featured advanced distributed processing, a distributed Ada database, and object-oriented design.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada is also used in other air traffic systems, e.g., the UK's next-generation Interim Future Area Control Tools Support (iFACTS) air traffic control system is designed and implemented using SPARK Ada.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] It is also used in the French TVM in-cab signalling system on the TGV high-speed rail system, and the metro suburban trains in Paris, London, Hong Kong and New York City.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Ada 95 revision of the language went beyond the Steelman requirements, targeting general-purpose systems in addition to embedded ones, and adding features supporting object-oriented programming.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada was first published in 1980 as an ANSI standard ANSI/**MIL-STD 1815**.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] As this very first version held many errors and inconsistencies, the revised edition was published in 1983 as ANSI/MIL-STD 1815A.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Without any further changes, it became an ISO standard in 1987.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This version of the language is commonly known as **Ada 83**, from the date of its adoption by ANSI, but is sometimes referred to also as **Ada 87**, from the date of its adoption by ISO.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] There is also a French translation; DIN translated it into German as DIN 66268 in 1988.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Work has continued on improving and updating the technical content of the Ada language.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] A Technical Corrigendum to Ada 95 was published in October 2001, and a major Amendment, ISO/IEC 8652:1995/Amd 1:2007 was published on March 9, 2007, commonly known as **Ada 2005** because work on the new standard was finished that year.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Ada-based SPARK technology has been made possible by the enabling characteristics of the Ada language, including its separation of specification and implementation via packages, its support for user-defined scalar types, and its support for composite type usage without resorting to pointers.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The Ada 2012 revision was especially important for SPARK, as its support for contracts as a part of the language permitted SPARK to be redesigned from the beginning towards fulfilling its goal of co-developing programs alongside their proofs of correctness.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] On May 2, 2023, the Ada community saw the formal approval of publication of the **Ada 2022** edition of the programming language standard.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Despite the names Ada 83, 95 etc., legally there is only one Ada standard, the last ISO/IEC standard: with the acceptance of a new standard version, the previous one becomes withdrawn.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The other names are informal ones referencing a certain edition.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Other related standards include ISO/IEC 8651-3:1988 *Information processing systems—Computer graphics—Graphical Kernel System (GKS) language bindings—Part 3: Ada*.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada is an ALGOL-like programming language featuring control structures with reserved words such as *if*, *then*, *else*, *while*, *for*, and so on.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] However, Ada also has many data structuring facilities and other abstractions which were not included in the original ALGOL 60, such as type definitions, records, pointers, and enumerations.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited from or inspired by Pascal.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada's type system is not based on a set of predefined primitive types but allows users to declare their own types.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This declaration in turn is not based on the internal representation of the type but on describing the goal which should be achieved.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] This allows the compiler to determine a suitable memory size for the type, and to check for violations of the type definition at compile time and run time (i.e., range violations, buffer overruns, type consistency, etc.).
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada supports numerical types defined by a range, modulo types, aggregate types (records and arrays), and enumeration types.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Access types define a reference to an instance of a specified type; untyped pointers are not permitted.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Special types provided by the language are task types and protected types.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] The predefined plus operator can only add values of the same type, so the expression is illegal.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Types can have modifiers such as *limited, abstract, private* etc.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Private types do not show their inner structure; objects of limited types cannot be copied.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 adds further features for object-oriented extension of types.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Ada is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] All standard constructs and deep-level early exit are supported, so the use of the also supported "go to" commands is seldom needed.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Among the parts of an Ada program are packages, procedures and functions.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Functions differ from procedures in that they must return a value.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Function calls cannot be used "as a statement", and their result must be assigned to a variable.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] However, since Ada 2012, functions are not required to be pure and may mutate their suitably declared parameters or the global state.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Packages, procedures and functions can nest to any depth, and each can also be the logical outermost block.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Each package, procedure or function can have its own declarations of constants, types, variables, and other procedures, functions and packages, which can be declared in any order.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] A pragma is a compiler directive that conveys information to the compiler to allow specific manipulating of compiled output.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Certain pragmas are built into the language, while others are implementation-specific.
[src:consumer-electronics/ada-programming-language] Examples of common usage of compiler pragmas would be to disable certain features, such as run-time type checking or array subscript boundary checking, or to instruct the compiler to insert object code instead of a function call (as C/C++ does with inline functions).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] It has historically specialized in software for the creation and publication of a wide range of content, including graphics, photography, illustration, animation, multimedia/video, motion pictures and print.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Its flagship products include Adobe Photoshop image editing software; Adobe Illustrator vector-based illustration software; Adobe Acrobat and the Portable Document Format (PDF); and a host of tools primarily for audio-visual content creation, editing, and publishing.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe offered a bundled solution of its products named Adobe Creative Suite, which evolved into a subscription-based offering named Adobe Creative Cloud.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The company also expanded into digital marketing software and in 2021 was considered one of the top global leaders in Customer Experience Management (CXM).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe was founded in December 1982 by John Warnock and Charles Geschke, who established the company after leaving Xerox PARC to develop and sell the PostScript page description language.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 1985, Apple Computer licensed PostScript for use in its LaserWriter printers, which helped spark the desktop publishing revolution.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] As of 2022, Adobe had more than 26,000 employees worldwide.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe also has major development operations in the United States in Newton, New York City, Arden Hills, Lehi, Seattle, Austin and San Francisco.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] It also has major development operations in Noida and Bangalore in India.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The company was started in John Warnock's garage.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The name of the company, Adobe, comes from Adobe Creek in Los Altos, California, a stream which ran behind Warnock's house.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The creek is named because of the type of clay found there (Adobe being a Spanish word for *Mudbrick*).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's corporate logo features a stylized "A" and was designed by graphic designer Marva Warnock, John Warnock's wife.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Steve Jobs attempted to buy the company for $5 million in 1982, but Warnock and Geschke refused.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Their investors urged them to work something out with Jobs, so they agreed to sell him shares worth 19 percent of the company.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Jobs paid a five-times multiple of their company's valuation at the time, plus a five-year license fee for PostScript, in advance.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The purchase and advance made Adobe the first company in the history of Silicon Valley to become profitable in its first year.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Warnock and Geschke considered various business options including a copy-service business and a turnkey system for office printing.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Then it chose to focus on developing specialized printing software and created the Adobe PostScript page description language.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] PostScript was the first international standard for computer printing as it included algorithms describing the letter-forms of many languages.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe added kanji printer products in 1988.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Warnock and Geschke were also able to bolster the credibility of PostScript by connecting with a typesetting manufacturer.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] They weren't able to work with Compugraphic, but then worked with Linotype to license the Helvetica and Times Roman fonts (through the Linotron 100).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] By 1987, PostScript had become the industry-standard printer language with more than 400 third-party software programs and licensing agreements with 19 printer companies.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's first products after PostScript were digital fonts which they released in a proprietary format called Type 1, worked on by Bill Paxton after he left Stanford.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Apple subsequently developed a competing standard, TrueType, which provided full scalability and precise control of the pixel pattern created by the font's outlines, and licensed it to Microsoft.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Starting in the mid-1980s, Adobe entered the consumer software market, starting with Adobe Illustrator, a vector-based drawing program for the Apple Macintosh.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Illustrator, which grew out of the firm's in-house font-development software, helped popularize PostScript-enabled laser printers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] By the mid-1990s, Adobe would acquire Photoshop from John and Thomas Knoll, FrameMaker from Frame Technology Corporation, and After Effects and PageMaker from Aldus, as well as develop Adobe Premiere, later known as Premiere Pro, in-house, initially releasing it in 1991.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Around the same time as the development of Illustrator, Adobe entered the NASDAQ Composite index in August 1986.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 1993, Adobe introduced the Portable Document Format, commonly shortened to the initialism PDF, and its Adobe Acrobat and Reader software.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Warnock originally developed the PDF under a code name, "The Camelot Project", using PostScript technology to create a widely available digital document format, able to display text, raster graphics, vector graphics, and fonts.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe kept the PDF as a proprietary file format from its introduction until 2008, when the PDF became an ISO international standard under ISO number ISO 32000-1:2008, though the PDF file format was free for viewers since its introduction.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] With its acquisition of Aldus, in addition to gaining PageMaker and After Effects, Adobe gained control over the TIFF file format for images.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The 2000s saw various developments for the company.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Its first notable acquisition in the decade was in 2002, when Adobe acquired Canadian company Accelio, also known as JetForm.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In May 2003, Adobe purchased audio editing and multitrack recording software Cool Edit Pro from Syntrillium Software for $16.5 million, as well as a large loop library called "Loopology".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe then renamed Cool Edit Pro to Adobe Audition.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] It was in 2003 that the company introduced the first version of Adobe Creative Suite, bundling its creative software into a single package.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] By April 2008, Adobe released Adobe Media Player.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On April 27, Adobe discontinued the development and sales of its older HTML/web development software, GoLive, in favor of Dreamweaver.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe offered a discount on Dreamweaver for GoLive users and supports those who still use GoLive with online tutorials and migration assistance.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On June 1, Adobe launched Acrobat.com, a series of web applications geared for collaborative work.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Creative Suite 4, which includes Design, Web, Production Premium, and Master Collection came out in October 2008 in six configurations at prices from about US$1,700 to $2,500 or by individual application.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The Windows version of Photoshop includes 64-bit processing.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On December 3, 2008, Adobe laid off 600 of its employees (8% of the worldwide staff) citing the weak economic environment.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On September 15, 2009, Adobe Systems announced that it would acquire online marketing and web analytics company Omniture for $1.8 billion.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The deal was completed on October 23, 2009.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Former Omniture products were integrated into the Adobe Marketing Cloud.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On November 10, 2009, the company laid off a further 680 employees.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's 2010 was marked by continuing arguments with Apple over the latter's non-support for Adobe Flash on its iPhone, iPad and other products.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Former Apple CEO Steve Jobs claimed that Flash was not reliable or secure enough, while Adobe executives have argued that Apple wishes to maintain control over the iOS platform.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In April 2010, Steve Jobs published a post titled *Thoughts on Flash* where he outlined his thoughts on Flash and the rise of HTML5.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In January 2011, Adobe acquired DemDex, Inc. with the intent of adding DemDex's audience-optimization software to its online marketing suite.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] At Photoshop World 2011, Adobe unveiled a new mobile photo service.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Carousel was a new application for iPhone, iPad, and Mac that used Photoshop Lightroom technology to allow users to adjust and fine-tune images on all platforms.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Carousel also allowed users to automatically sync, share and browse photos.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The service was later renamed "Adobe Revel".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Later that same year in October, Adobe acquired Nitobi Software, the maker of the mobile application development framework *PhoneGap*.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] As part of the acquisition, the source code of PhoneGap was submitted to the Apache Foundation, where it became Apache Cordova.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In November 2011, Adobe announced that it would cease development of Flash for mobile devices following version 11.1.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Instead, it would focus on HTML5 for mobile devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In December 2011, Adobe announced that it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire privately held Efficient Frontier.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In December 2012, Adobe opened a new 280,000-square-foot (26,000 m2) corporate campus in Lehi, Utah.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 2013, Adobe endured a major security breach.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Vast portions of the source code for the company's software were stolen and posted online and over 150 million records of Adobe's customers were made readily available for download.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 2012, about 40 million sets of payment card information were compromised by a hack at Adobe.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] A class-action lawsuit alleging that the company suppressed employee compensation was filed against Adobe, and three other Silicon Valley–based companies in a California federal district court in 2013.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In May 2014, it was revealed the four companies, Adobe, Apple, Google, and Intel had reached an agreement with the plaintiffs, 64,000 employees of the four companies, to pay a sum of $324.5 million to settle the suit.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] 2011 saw the company first introduce Adobe Creative Cloud, a $600/year subscription plan to its creative software as opposed to a one-time perpetual license payment which could often top $2000 for creative professionals.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Reception to the mandatory subscriptions for future Adobe software was mostly negative, despite some positive testimonies on the move from customers and Adobe's attraction of 500,000 Creative Cloud subscribers by the service's first year.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In March 2018, at Adobe Summit, the company and Nvidia announced their association to upgrade their AI and profound learning innovations.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] They planned to streamline Adobe Sensei AI and machine learning structure for Nvidia GPUs.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe and Nvidia had cooperated for 10 years on GPU quickening.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] This incorporates Sensei-powered features, e.g. auto lip-sync in Adobe Character Animator CC and face-aware editing in Photoshop CC, and also cloud-based AI/ML items and features, for example, picture investigation for Adobe Stock and Lightroom CC and auto-labeling in Adobe Experience Supervisor.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe further spent its time from 2018 to 2023 acquiring more companies to boost both Creative Cloud and the Adobe Experience Cloud, a software suite which increased business.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] These included e-commerce services provider Magento Commerce from private equity firm Permira for $1.68 billion in June 2018, Marketo for $4.75 billion in 2018, Allegorithmic in 2019 for just under $160 million, and Workfront in December 2020 for $1.5 billion.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] 2021 additionally saw Adobe add payment services to its e-commerce platforms in an attempt to compete with Shopify, accepting both credit cards and PayPal.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In July 2020, as the United States presidential elections approached, the software giant imposed a ban on the political ads features on its digital advertising sales platform.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On November 9, 2020, Adobe announced it would spend US$1.5 billion to acquire Workfront, a provider of marketing collaboration software.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The acquisition was completed in early December 2020.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On August 19, 2021, Adobe announced it had entered into a definitive agreement to acquire Frame.io, a leading cloud-based video collaboration platform.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The transaction is valued at $1.275 billion and closed during the fourth quarter of Adobe's 2021 fiscal year.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe announced a $20 billion acquisition of Figma, an Adobe XD competitor, in September 2022, its largest to date.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Regulatory scrutiny from the US and European Union began shortly after due to concerns that Adobe, already a major player in the design software market with XD, would have too much control if it also owned Figma.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] At the time of the announcement to acquire Figma, Adobe's share over the creative software market and design-software market was almost a monopoly.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In December 2023, the two companies called off their merger, citing the regulatory challenges as a sign to both that the deal was not likely to be approved.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe paid Figma a $1 billion termination fee per their merger agreement.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On June 17, 2024, the US Federal Trade Commission together with the US Department of Justice filed a lawsuit against Adobe for its subscription business model practice, citing hidden termination fees and the company pushing customers towards more expensive plans.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On March 13, 2026, the lawsuit was settled out of court for $150M.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In June 2024, after facing backlash for its changes to the terms of service, Adobe updated them to explicitly pledge it will not use customer data to train its artificial intelligence models.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In November 2025, Adobe Inc. announced its agreement to acquire Semrush for $1.9 billion.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In March 2026, Adobe announced Shantanu Narayen would step down from his position as CEO after 18 years.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Narayen was expected to stay on until a new CEO was identified and remain as chairman.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe, among other software companies, were in investor crosshairs amid concerns about competitive threats from increased AI adoption.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On March 16, 2026, Adobe and NVIDIA announced a strategic partnership to deliver next-generation Adobe Firefly models and agentic workflows.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The collaboration spans AI model development, 3D product visualization, document intelligence, and cloud media workflows, with a joint go-to-market strategy targeting enterprise customers through Adobe's Firefly Foundry platform.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe Color, Photoshop Express, Acrobat.com, Behance and Adobe Express.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] A microstock agency that presently provides over 57 million high-resolution, royalty-free images and videos available to license (via subscription or credit purchase methods).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 2015, Adobe acquired **Fotolia**, a stock content marketplace founded in 2005 by Thibaud Elziere, Oleg Tscheltzoff, and Patrick Chassany which operated in 23 countries.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] It was run as a stand-alone website until 2019, but has since been integrated into Adobe Stock.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] A family of content, development, and customer relationship management products, with what Adobe calls the "next generation" of its Sensei artificial intelligence and machine learning framework, introduced in March 2019.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe has been criticized for its pricing practices, with retail prices being up to twice as much in non-US countries.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] After Adobe revealed the pricing for the Creative Suite 3 Master Collection, which was £1,000 higher for European customers, a petition to protest over "unfair pricing" was published and signed by 10,000 users.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In June 2009, Adobe further increased its prices in the UK by 10% in spite of weakening of the pound against the dollar, and UK users were not allowed to buy from the US store.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's Reader and Flash programs were listed on "The 10 most hated programs of all time" article by *TechRadar*.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Hackers have exploited vulnerabilities in Adobe programs, such as Adobe Reader, to gain unauthorized access to computers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's Flash Player has also been criticized for, among other things, suffering from performance, memory usage and security problems.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] A report by security researchers from Kaspersky Lab criticized Adobe for producing the products having top 10 security vulnerabilities.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Observers noted that Adobe was spying on its customers by including spyware in the Creative Suite 3 software and quietly sending user data to a firm named Omniture.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] When users became aware, Adobe explained what the suspicious software did and admitted that they: "could and should do a better job taking security concerns into account".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] When a security flaw was later discovered in Photoshop CS5, Adobe sparked outrage by saying it would leave the flaw unpatched, so anyone who wanted to use the software securely would have to pay for an upgrade.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Following a fierce backlash Adobe decided to provide the software patch.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe has been criticized for pushing unwanted software including third-party browser toolbars and free virus scanners, usually as part of the Flash update process, and for pushing a third-party scareware program designed to scare users into paying for unneeded system repairs.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] On October 3, 2013, the company initially revealed that 2.9 million customers' sensitive and personal data was stolen in a security breach which included encrypted credit card information.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe later admitted that 38 million active users have been affected and the attackers obtained access to their IDs and encrypted passwords, as well as to many inactive Adobe accounts.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The company did not make it clear if all the personal information was encrypted, such as email addresses and physical addresses, though data privacy laws in 44 states require this information to be encrypted.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In late 2013 a 3.8 GB file stolen from Adobe and containing 152 million usernames, reversibly encrypted passwords and unencrypted password hints was posted on AnonNews.org.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] LastPass, a password security firm, said that Adobe failed to use best practices for securing the passwords and has not salted them.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Another security firm, Sophos, showed that Adobe used a weak encryption method permitting the recovery of a lot of information with very little effort.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] According to IT expert Simon Bain, Adobe has failed its customers and 'should hang their heads in shame'.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Many of the credit cards were tied to the Creative Cloud software-by-subscription service.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe offered its affected US customers a free membership in a credit monitoring service, but no similar arrangements have been made for non-US customers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] When a data breach occurs in the US, penalties depend on the state where the victim resides, not where the company is based.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] After stealing the customers' data, cyber-thieves also accessed Adobe's source code repository, likely in mid-August 2013.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Because hackers acquired copies of the source code of Adobe proprietary products, they could find and exploit any potential weaknesses in its security, computer experts warned.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Security researcher Alex Holden, chief information security officer of Hold Security, characterized this Adobe breach, which affected Acrobat, ColdFusion and numerous other applications, as "one of the worst in US history".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe also announced that hackers stole parts of the source code of Photoshop, which according to commentators could allow programmers to copy its engineering techniques and would make it easier to pirate Adobe's expensive products.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Published on a server of a Russian-speaking hacker group, the "disclosure of encryption algorithms, other security schemes, and software vulnerabilities can be used to bypass protections for individual and corporate data" and may have opened the gateway to new generation zero-day attacks.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Hackers already used ColdFusion exploits to make off with usernames and encrypted passwords of PR Newswire's customers, which has been tied to the Adobe security breach.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] They also used a ColdFusion exploit to breach Washington state court and expose up to 200,000 Social Security numbers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 1994, Adobe acquired Aldus Corp., a software vendor that sold FreeHand, a competing product.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] FreeHand was direct competition to Adobe Illustrator, Adobe's flagship vector-graphics editor.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The Federal Trade Commission (FTC) intervened and forced Adobe to sell FreeHand back to Altsys, and also banned Adobe from buying back FreeHand or any similar program for the next 10 years (1994–2004).
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Altsys was then bought by Macromedia, which released versions 5 to 11.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] When Adobe acquired Macromedia in December 2005, it stalled development of FreeHand in 2007, effectively rendering it obsolete.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] With FreeHand and Illustrator, Adobe controlled the only two products that competed in the professional illustration program market for Macintosh operating systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In 2011, a group of 5,000 FreeHand graphic designers convened under the banner *Free FreeHand*, and filed a civil antitrust complaint in the US District Court for the Northern District of California against Adobe.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe had no response to the claims and the lawsuit was eventually settled.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] The FreeHand community believes Adobe should release the product to an open-source community if it cannot update it internally.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe's software FTP server still contains a directory for FreeHand, but it is empty.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In April 2021, Adobe received criticism from Twitter users for the company's cancellation fees after a customer shared a tweet showing they had been charged a $291.45 cancellation fee for their Adobe Creative Cloud subscription.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Many also showed their cancellation fees for Adobe Creative Cloud, with this leading to many encouraging piracy of Adobe products and/or purchase of alternatives with lower prices or using free and open-source software instead.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Furthermore, there have been reports that with changing subscriptions it is possible to avoid paying this fee.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Department of Justice and the FTC filed a lawsuit against Adobe and two of its executives in June 2024, alleging that the company's deceptive subscription practices and cancellation policies violated the Restore Online Shoppers' Confidence Act.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] According to the lawsuit, the company purportedly used small text disclosures, optional input fields, and complex web of links to obscure a concealed early termination fee.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] This fee reportedly amounted to fifty percent of the remaining value of annual contracts for users who chose to cancel early in the first year, resulting in significant penalties.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Customers who tried to cancel services by contacting customer service faced obstacles, including dropped calls and multiple transfers between representatives; others continued to be billed by Adobe, under the mistaken belief that they had successfully ended their subscriptions.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] In March 2026, Adobe agreed to pay $75 million to settle a lawsuit with the U.S.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Department of Justice over allegations that the company failed to clearly disclose cancellation fees associated with its subscription plans.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-inc] Adobe responded the following day clarifying that it will not use user data to train generative AI or take users work as its own; however, it neglected to respond to the part in the TOS that gives Adobe the ability to view or use work that is contracted under an NDA.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Adobe offered individual products as well as software suites containing several products (such as Adobe Creative Suite or Adobe eLearning Suite) with a perpetual software license.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Adobe first announced the Creative Cloud in October 2011.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Another version of Adobe Creative Suite was released the following year.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] On May 6, 2013, Adobe announced that they would not release new versions of the Creative Suite and that future versions of its software would be available only through the Creative Cloud.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The first new versions made only for the Creative Cloud were released on June 17, 2013.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The Adobe Creative Cloud retains many of the features of Adobe Creative Suite and introduces new features; foremost is the instant availability of upgrades, saving to the cloud, and easier sharing.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] In June 2014, the company announced 14 new versions of the Creative Cloud essential desktop tools, four new mobile apps, and the availability of creative hardware for enterprise, education and photography customers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The video disc authoring program Adobe Encore and the web-focused bitmap editor Adobe Fireworks were both discontinued by Adobe in 2013, but were still available as downloads via Creative Cloud until May 2019.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The following contains the services found on Creative Cloud.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The change from perpetual licenses to a subscription model was met with significant criticism.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Although Adobe's cloud-based model caused disagreement and uncertainty, and incited annoyance and conflict, a survey by CNET and Jefferies revealed that despite complaints most of its 1.4 million subscribers plan to renew.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Shifting to a subscription-based licensing model using cloud computing, Adobe announced more frequent feature updates to its products and the eschewing of their traditional release cycles.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Customers must pay a monthly subscription fee.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Consequently, if subscribers cancel or stop paying, they will lose access to all or some of the software as well as the ability to open work saved in its proprietary file formats.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Creative Cloud has been described as an example of enshittification.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Although investors applauded the move, many customers reacted negatively.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] This shift has been met with mixed reviews by both corporations and independent designers, with many people expressing their displeasure on the web and through multiple Internet petitions.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Among these was a Change.org petition which reached over 30,000 signatures within a few weeks of the announcement.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Creative Cloud has been criticized for broken file syncing, one of its core features.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] In May 2013 Adobe announced that it was suspending the file-sync desktop preview "for the next couple of weeks".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Reviewers of Creative Cloud were disappointed with the functionality of the cloud storage and were "far from convinced by Adobe's subscription model".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Some users were concerned that they would be forced to upgrade their computer hardware when it is no longer supported by the current version of the Creative Cloud software.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Some of their customers experienced a loss of trust in Adobe as a company and an attendant rise in anxiety.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] In May 2014 the service was interrupted for over a day due to a login outage leaving graphics professionals locked out of Creative Cloud.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Adobe apologized for this global Creative Cloud failure.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] When initially asked whether customers would be compensated, the company's Customer Service responded: "We cannot offer compensation for the outage.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] I'm so sorry again for the frustration." Adobe later announced that it would review compensation on "a case by case basis".
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The outage was heavily criticized, as was Adobe's subscription-based licensing model in general.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Online articles began offering examples of replacements for Adobe products, with competing products directly offering alternatives, and launching promotions for dissatisfied Adobe customers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Although Creative Cloud was expected to curtail the piracy of Photoshop, which is one of the most pirated pieces of software, Creative Cloud was hacked and its applications were made available via unauthorized means a day after it officially launched.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Adobe claimed that the subscription payment plan would make its software more accessible to users who previously pirated it.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] On May 14, 2019, some Creative Cloud users received emails from Adobe stating that licenses to previous versions of Creative Cloud applications had been terminated and that users could face civil action from third parties if they did not update the software on their personal computers.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] A representative from Adobe confirmed the letter's authenticity.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] The situation prompted renewed criticism of Adobe's subscription-only business model.
[src:consumer-electronics/adobe-stock] Adobe users who sign NDAs could be in trouble after Adobe updated its terms of service to force users to share their content with Adobe, a clause that will compromise any NDA.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There are various types of air conditioners.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In hot weather, air conditioning can prevent heat stroke, dehydration due to excessive sweating, electrolyte imbalance, kidney failure, and other issues due to hyperthermia.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] An estimated 190,000 heat-related deaths are averted annually owing to air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners increase productivity in hot climates, and historians rank air conditioning as a key factor that shaped postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As of 2022, air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners, which typically use vapor-compression refrigeration, range in size from small units used in vehicles or single rooms to massive units that can cool large buildings.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air source heat pumps, which can be used for heating as well as cooling, are becoming increasingly common in cooler climates.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] According to the International Energy Agency (IEA) 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used globally in 2016.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The United Nations has called for the technology to be made more sustainable to mitigate climate change and for the use of alternatives, such as passive cooling, evaporative cooling, selective shading, windcatchers, and thermal insulation.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning dates back to prehistory.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Double-walled living quarters, with a gap between the two walls to encourage air flow, were found in the ancient city of Hamoukar, in modern Syria.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Ancient Egyptian buildings also used a wide variety of passive air-conditioning techniques.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] These became widespread from the Iberian Peninsula through North Africa, the Middle East, and Northern India.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Passive techniques remained widespread until the 20th century when they fell out of fashion and were replaced by powered air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Using information from engineering studies of traditional buildings, passive techniques are being revived and modified for 21st-century architectural designs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioners allow the building's indoor environment to remain relatively constant, largely independent of changes in external weather conditions and internal heat loads.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They also enable deep plan buildings to be created and have allowed people to live comfortably in hotter parts of the world.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1558, Giambattista della Porta described a method of chilling ice to temperatures far below its freezing point by mixing it with potassium nitrate (then called "nitre") in his popular science book *Natural Magic*.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel demonstrated "Turning Summer into Winter" for James I of England, chilling part of the Great Hall of Westminster Abbey with an apparatus of troughs and vats.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1758, Benjamin Franklin and John Hadley, a chemistry professor at the University of Cambridge, conducted experiments applying the principle of evaporation as a means to cool an object rapidly.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Franklin and Hadley confirmed that the evaporation of highly volatile liquids (such as alcohol and ether) could be used to drive down the temperature of an object past the freezing point of water.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They experimented with the bulb of a mercury-in-glass thermometer as their object.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They used a bellows to speed up the evaporation.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They lowered the temperature of the thermometer bulb down to −14 °C (7 °F) while the ambient temperature was 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Franklin noted that soon after they passed the freezing point of water 0 °C (32 °F), a thin film of ice formed on the surface of the thermometer's bulb and that the ice mass was about 6 mm (1⁄4 in) thick when they stopped the experiment upon reaching −14 °C (7 °F).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The 19th century included many developments in compression technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1820, English scientist and inventor Michael Faraday discovered that compressing and liquefying ammonia could chill air when the liquefied ammonia was allowed to evaporate.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1842, Florida physician John Gorrie used compressor technology to create ice, which he used to cool air for his patients in his hospital in Apalachicola, Florida.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] He hoped to eventually use his ice-making machine to regulate the temperature of buildings.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] He envisioned centralized air conditioning that could cool entire cities.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Gorrie was granted a patent in 1851, but following the death of his main backer, he was not able to realize his invention.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1851, James Harrison created the first mechanical ice-making machine in Geelong, Australia, and was granted a patent for an ether vapor-compression refrigeration system in 1855 that produced three tons of ice per day.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1860, Harrison established a second ice company.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] He later entered the debate over competing against the American advantage of ice-refrigerated beef sales to the United Kingdom.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This innovation made the systems more compact and suitable for urban environments.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] By 1896, his factory produced 'dry air cooling apparatuses' specifically designed for the cooling and dehumidification of hospitals, theaters, large public halls, and even residential rooms, several years before the widespread commercialization of modern air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This system operated by using an electric motor-driven ammonia compressor to chill a secondary refrigerant, typically brine (salt water).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This cold brine was circulated through pipes to a 'dry air cooling unit' (a precursor to the modern air handler), where a fan forced ambient air over the chilled coils.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This process not only lowered the temperature but also dehumidified the air by condensing moisture on the cold surfaces.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Electricity made the development of effective units possible.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Carrier built what is considered the first modern electrical air conditioning unit.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1902, he installed his first air-conditioning system in the Sackett-Wilhelms Lithographing & Publishing Company in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] He patented "air conditioning" in 1906, and by 1914, the first domestic (or "residential") air conditioner was installed.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] His invention controlled both the temperature and humidity, which helped maintain consistent paper dimensions and ink alignment at the printing plant.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Later, together with six other employees, Carrier formed The Carrier Air Conditioning Company of America, a business that in 2020, employed 53,000 people and was valued at $18.6 billion.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Cramer of Charlotte, North Carolina, was exploring ways to add moisture to the air in his textile mill.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Cramer coined the term "air conditioning" in a patent claim which he filed that year, where he suggested that air conditioning was analogous to "water conditioning", then a well-known process for making textiles easier to process.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] He combined moisture with ventilation to "condition" and change the air in the factories, thus controlling the humidity that is necessary in textile plants.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Willis Carrier adopted the term and incorporated it into the name of his company.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Domestic air conditioning soon took off.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1914, the first domestic air conditioning was installed in Minneapolis in the home of Charles Gilbert Gates.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It is, however, possible that the considerable device (c.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Sherman developed what would become the most common type of individual room air conditioner: one designed to sit on a window ledge.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The units went on sale in 1932 at US$10,000 to $50,000 (the equivalent of $200,000 to $1,200,000 in 2025.) A year later, the first air conditioning systems for cars were offered for sale.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Chrysler Motors introduced the first practical semi-portable air conditioning unit in 1935, and Packard became the first automobile manufacturer to offer an air conditioning unit in its cars in 1939.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Innovations in the latter half of the 20th century allowed more ubiquitous air conditioner use.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1945, Robert Sherman of Lynn, Massachusetts, invented a portable, in-window air conditioner that cooled, heated, humidified, dehumidified, and filtered the air.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The first inverter air conditioners were released in 1980–1981.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1954, Ned Cole, a 1939 architecture graduate from the University of Texas at Austin, developed the first experimental "suburb" with inbuilt air conditioning in each house.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In addition, researchers from UT's Health Service and Psychology Department studied the effects on the "artificially cooled humans." One of the more amusing discoveries was that each family reported being troubled with scorpions, the leading theory being that scorpions sought cool, shady places.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Other reported changes in lifestyle were that mothers baked more, families ate heavier foods, and they were more apt to choose hot drinks.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioner adoption tends to increase above around $10,000 (circa 2021) annual household income in warmer areas.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Global GDP growth explains around 85% of increased air condition adoption by 2050, while the remaining 15% can be explained by climate change.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The urban heat island effect was first scientifically noted by Luke Howard in the 1810s, who described London being several degrees warmer than its rural surroundings at night.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The phenomenon gained attention in the late 1960s, mainly in Japan and North America.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] From the late 1980s to early 2010s, studies began to link air conditioners to the urban heat island effect.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The phenomenon was observed in various cities such as Tokyo and Houston.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As of 2016, an estimated 1.6 billion air conditioning units were used worldwide, with over half of them in China and the United States, and with a total cooling capacity of 11,675 gigawatts.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The International Energy Agency predicted in 2018 that the number of air conditioning units would grow to around 4 billion units by 2050 and that the total cooling capacity would grow to around 23,000 GW, with the biggest increases in India and China.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Between 1995 and 2004, the proportion of urban households in China with air conditioners increased from 8% to 70%.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Between 2010 and 2023, air conditioner use in India tripled to 24 units per 100 households, with the most ownership in Haryana, Chandigarh, Rajasthan, and Delhi and the least in Meghalaya, Tripura, Manipur, and Himachal Pradesh.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As of 2015, nearly 100 million homes in the United States, or about 87% of US households, had air conditioning systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 2019, it was estimated that 90% of new single-family homes constructed in the US included air conditioning, ranging from 99% in the South to 62% in the West.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As of 2025, roughly half of homes in Italy, 40 percent of homes in Spain, and 20 to 25 percent of homes in France had air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Cooling in traditional air conditioner systems is accomplished using the vapor-compression cycle, which uses a refrigerant's forced circulation and phase change between gas and liquid to transfer heat.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The vapor-compression cycle can occur within a unitary, or packaged piece of equipment, or within a chiller that is connected to terminal cooling equipment (such as a fan coil unit in an air handler) on its evaporator side and heat rejection equipment such as a cooling tower on its condenser side.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] An air source heat pump shares many components with an air conditioning system, but includes a reversing valve, which allows the unit to be used to heat as well as cool a space.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning equipment will reduce the absolute humidity of the air processed by the system if the surface of the evaporator coil is significantly cooler than the dew point of the surrounding air.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] An air conditioner designed for an occupied space will typically achieve a 30% to 60% relative humidity in the occupied space.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Most modern air-conditioning systems feature a dehumidification mode, in which the compressor runs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] At the same time, the fan is slowed to reduce the evaporator temperature and condense more water.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Free cooling can sometimes be selected when the external air is cooler than the internal air.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In this case, the compressor does not need to be used, resulting in high cooling efficiencies for these times.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This may also be combined with seasonal thermal energy storage.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Some air conditioning systems can reverse the refrigeration cycle and act as an air source heat pump, thus heating instead of cooling the indoor environment.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They are also commonly referred to as "reverse cycle air conditioners".
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The heat pump is significantly more energy-efficient than electric resistance heating, because it moves energy from air or groundwater to the heated space and the heat from purchased electrical energy.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] When the heat pump is in heating mode, the indoor evaporator coil switches roles and becomes the condenser coil, producing heat and the outdoor condenser unit also switches roles to serve as the evaporator and discharges cold air (colder than the ambient outdoor air).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Most air source heat pumps become less efficient in outdoor temperatures lower than 4 °C or 40 °F.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This is partly because ice forms on the outdoor unit's heat exchanger coil, which blocks air flow over the coil.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] To compensate for this, the heat pump system must temporarily switch back into the regular air conditioning mode to switch the outdoor evaporator coil back to being the condenser coil, so it can heat up and defrost.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Therefore, some heat pump systems will have electric resistance heating in the indoor air path that is activated only in this mode to compensate for the temporary indoor air cooling, which would otherwise be uncomfortable in the winter.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Newer models have improved cold-weather performance, with efficient heating capacity down to −14 °F (−26 °C).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] However, there is always a chance that the humidity that condenses on the heat exchanger of the outdoor unit could freeze, even in models that have improved cold-weather performance, requiring a defrosting cycle to be performed.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In this case, the heat pump is used efficiently during milder temperatures, and the system is switched to the conventional heat source when the outdoor temperature is lower.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The coefficient of performance (COP) of an air conditioning system is a ratio of useful heating or cooling provided to the work required.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Higher COPs equate to lower operating costs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The COP usually exceeds 1; however, the exact value is highly dependent on operating conditions, especially absolute temperature and relative temperature between sink and system, and is often graphed or averaged against expected conditions.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioner equipment power in the U.S. is often described in terms of "tons of refrigeration", with each approximately equal to the cooling power of one short ton (2,000 pounds (910 kg) of ice melting in a 24-hour period.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The value is equal to 12,000 BTUIT per hour, or 3,517 watts.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Residential central air systems are usually from 1 to 5 tons (3.5 to 18 kW) in capacity.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The efficiency of air conditioners is often rated by the seasonal energy efficiency ratio (SEER), which is defined by the Air Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration Institute in its 2008 standard AHRI 210/240, *Performance Rating of Unitary Air-Conditioning and Air-Source Heat Pump Equipment*.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A similar standard is the European seasonal energy efficiency ratio (ESEER).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Efficiency is strongly affected by the humidity of the air to be cooled.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Dehumidifying the air before attempting to cool it can reduce subsequent cooling costs by as much as 90 percent.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Thus, reducing dehumidifying costs can materially affect overall air conditioning costs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This type of controller uses an infrared LED to relay commands from a remote control to the air conditioner.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The output of the infrared LED (like that of any infrared remote) is invisible to the human eye because its wavelength is beyond the range of visible light (940 nm).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This system is commonly used on mini-split air conditioners because it is simple and portable.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Some window and ducted central air conditioners uses it as well.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A wired controller, also called a "wired thermostat," is a device that controls an air conditioner by switching heating or cooling on or off.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It uses different sensors to measure temperatures and actuate control operations.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Mechanical thermostats commonly use bimetallic strips, converting a temperature change into mechanical displacement, to actuate control of the air conditioner.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Electronic thermostats, instead, use a thermistor or other semiconductor sensor, processing temperature change as electronic signals to control the air conditioner.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] These controllers are usually used in apartments, hospitals, offices and hotel rooms, because they are permanently installed into a wall and hard-wired directly into the air conditioner unit, eliminating the need for batteries.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Ductless systems (often mini-split, though there are now ducted mini-split) typically supply conditioned and heated air to a single or a few rooms of a building, without ducts and in a decentralized manner.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Multi-zone or multi-split systems are a common application of ductless systems and allow up to eight rooms (zones or locations) to be conditioned independently from each other, each with its indoor unit and simultaneously from a single outdoor unit.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The first mini-split system was sold in 1961 by Toshiba in Japan, and the first wall-mounted mini-split air conditioner was sold in 1968 in Japan by Mitsubishi Electric, where small home sizes motivated their development.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The Mitsubishi model was the first air conditioner with a cross-flow fan.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In 1969, the first mini-split air conditioner was sold in the US.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Multi-zone ductless systems were invented by Daikin in 1973, and variable refrigerant flow systems (which can be thought of as larger multi-split systems) were also invented by Daikin in 1982.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The outdoor and indoor units can be spread across the building.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Variable refrigerant flow indoor units can also be turned off individually in unused spaces.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The lower start-up power of VRF's DC inverter compressors and their inherent DC power requirements also allow VRF solar-powered heat pumps to be run using DC-providing solar panels.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Split-system central air conditioners consist of two heat exchangers, an outside unit (the condenser) from which heat is rejected to the environment and an internal heat exchanger (the evaporator, or Fan Coil Unit, FCU) with the piped refrigerant being circulated between the two.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The FCU is then connected to the spaces to be cooled by ventilation ducts.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Floor standing air conditioners are similar to this type of air conditioner but sit within spaces that need cooling.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The chilled water is cooled by chillers in the plant, which uses a refrigeration cycle to cool water, often transferring its heat to the atmosphere even in liquid-cooled chillers through the use of cooling towers.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A portable system has an indoor unit on wheels connected to an outdoor unit via flexible pipes, similar to a permanently fixed installed unit (such as a ductless split air conditioner).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Hose systems, which can be *monoblock* or *air-to-air*, are vented to the outside via air ducts.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The *monoblock* type collects the water in a bucket or tray and stops when full.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The *air-to-air* type re-evaporates the water, discharges it through the ducted hose, and can run continuously.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Many but not all portable units draw indoor air and expel it outdoors through a single duct, negatively impacting their overall cooling efficiency.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Many portable air conditioners come with heat as well as a dehumidification function.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The packaged terminal air conditioner (PTAC), through-the-wall, and window air conditioners are similar.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] These units are installed on a window frame or on a wall opening.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The unit usually has an internal partition separating its indoor and outdoor sides, which contain the unit's condenser and evaporator, respectively.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] PTAC systems may be adapted to provide heating in cold weather, either directly by using an electric strip, gas, or other heaters, or by reversing the refrigerant flow to heat the interior and draw heat from the exterior air, converting the air conditioner into a heat pump.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] They may be installed in a wall opening with the help of a special sleeve on the wall and a custom grill that is flush with the wall and window air conditioners can also be installed in a window, but without a custom grill.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Packaged air conditioners (also known as self-contained units) are central systems that integrate into a single housing all the components of a split central system, and deliver air, possibly through ducts, to the spaces to be cooled.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Depending on their construction the units may be kept outdoors or indoors; draw the air to be conditioned from inside or outside a building and be water or air-cooled.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Often, outdoor units are air-cooled while indoor units are liquid-cooled using a cooling tower.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This compressor consists of a crankcase, crankshaft, piston rod, piston, piston ring, cylinder head and valves.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This compressor uses two interleaving scrolls to compress the refrigerant. it consists of one fixed and one orbiting scrolls.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This type of compressor is more efficient because it has 70 percent less moving parts than a reciprocating compressor.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This compressor use two very closely meshing spiral rotors to compress the gas.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The gas enters at the suction side and moves through the threads as the screws rotate.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The meshing rotors force the gas through the compressor, and the gas exits at the end of the screws.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The working area is the inter-lobe volume between the male and female rotors.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It is larger at the intake end, and decreases along the length of the rotors until the exhaust port.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This change in volume is the compression.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There are several ways to modulate the cooling capacity in refrigeration or air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The most common in air conditioning are: on-off cycling, hot gas bypass, use or not of liquid injection, manifold configurations of multiple compressors, mechanical modulation (also called digital), and inverter technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Hot gas bypass involves injecting a quantity of gas from discharge to the suction side.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The compressor will keep operating at the same speed, but due to the bypass, the refrigerant mass flow circulating with the system is reduced, and thus the cooling capacity is also reduced.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This naturally causes the compressor to run uselessly during the periods when the bypass is operating.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity varies between 0 and 100%.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Several compressors can be installed in the system to provide the peak cooling capacity.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Each compressor can run or not in order to stage the cooling capacity of the unit.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The turn down capacity is either 0/33/66 or 100% for a trio configuration and either 0/50 or 100% for a tandem.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This internal mechanical capacity modulation is based on periodic compression process with a control valve, the two scroll set move apart stopping the compression for a given time period.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This method varies refrigerant flow by changing the average time of compression, but not the actual speed of the motor.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Despite an excellent turndown ratio – from 10 to 100% of the cooling capacity, mechanically modulated scrolls have high energy consumption as the motor continuously runs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This system uses a variable-frequency drive (also called an Inverter) to control the speed of the compressor.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The refrigerant flow rate is changed by the change in the speed of the compressor.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The turn down ratio depends on the system configuration and manufacturer.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It modulates from 15 or 25% up to 100% at full capacity with a single inverter from 12 to 100% with a hybrid tandem.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This method is the most efficient way to modulate an air conditioner's capacity.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It is up to 58% more efficient than a fixed speed system.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Heat waves are the most lethal type of weather phenomenon in the United States.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A 2020 study found that areas with lower use of air conditioning correlated with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The August 2003 France heatwave resulted in approximately 15,000 deaths, where 80% of the victims were over 75 years old.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In response, the French government required all retirement homes to have at least one air-conditioned room at 25 °C (77 °F) per floor during heatwaves.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A 2021 report estimated that around 345,000 people aged 65 and older died in 2019 from the heat, which is preventable with air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning (including filtration, humidification, cooling and disinfection) can be used to provide a clean, safe, hypoallergenic atmosphere in hospital operating rooms and other environments where proper atmosphere is critical to patient safety and well-being.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It is sometimes recommended for home use by people with allergies, especially mold.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] However, poorly maintained water cooling towers can promote the growth and spread of microorganisms such as *Legionella pneumophila*, the infectious agent responsible for Legionnaires' disease.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As long as the cooling tower is kept clean (usually by means of a chlorine treatment), these health hazards can be avoided or reduced.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The state of New York has codified requirements for registration, maintenance, and testing of cooling towers to protect against Legionella.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] First designed to benefit targeted industries such as the press as well as large factories, the invention quickly spread to public agencies and administrations with studies with claims of increased productivity close to 24% in places equipped with air conditioning.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning contributed to the economic development of the American South after the 1950s by enabling industrial activities in hot climates and supporting the expansion of white-collar work in cooled office spaces.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It also influenced urban sprawl and commuting patterns, as air-conditioned vehicles made suburban development more viable.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Historians rank air conditioning among key factors shaping postwar metropolitan growth, alongside highways, automobiles, shopping malls, and suburban housing.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning caused various shifts in demography, notably that of the United States starting from the 1970s.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In the US, the birth rate was lower in the spring than during other seasons until the 1970s but this difference then declined since then.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As of 2007, the Sun Belt contained 30% of the total US population while it was inhabited by 24% of Americans at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Moreover, the summer mortality rate in the US, which had been higher in regions subject to a heat wave during the summer, also evened out.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The spread of the use of air conditioning acts as a main driver for the growth of global demand of electricity.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A 2020 survey found that an estimated 88% of all US households use AC, increasing to 93% when solely looking at homes built between 2010 and 2020.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning used about 7% of global electricity in 2022, and emitted 3% of greenhouse gas.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There is some push to increase the energy efficiency of air conditioners.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) and the IEA found that if air conditioners could be twice as effective as now, 460 billion tons of GHG could be cut over 40 years.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The UNEP and IEA also recommended legislation to decrease the use of hydrofluorocarbons, better building insulation, and more sustainable temperature-controlled food supply chains going forward.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Refrigerants have also caused and continue to cause serious environmental issues, including ozone depletion and climate change, as several countries have not yet ratified the Kigali Amendment to reduce the consumption and production of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] CFCs and HCFCs refrigerants such as R-12 and R-22, respectively, used within air conditioners have caused damage to the ozone layer, and hydrofluorocarbon refrigerants such as R-410A and R-404A, which were designed to replace CFCs and HCFCs, are instead exacerbating climate change.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Both issues happen due to the venting of refrigerant to the atmosphere, such as during repairs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] HFO refrigerants, used in some if not most new equipment, solve both issues with an ozone damage potential (ODP) of zero and a much lower global warming potential (GWP) in the single or double digits vs. the three or four digits of hydrofluorocarbons.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Hydrofluorocarbons would have raised global temperatures by around 0.3–0.5 °C (0.5–0.9 °F) by 2100 without the Kigali Amendment.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] With the Kigali Amendment, the increase of global temperatures by 2100 due to hydrofluorocarbons is predicted to be around 0.06 °C (0.1 °F).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Air conditioning units also contribute to pollution as they are difficult to disassemble or repair.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Separating metal and plastic at the end of a unit's life cycle is also costly and not practical, meaning units are frequently disposed of.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Several journalists say it is an *air conditioning paradox* that arises from the usage of air conditioners to adapt to the effects of climate change, leading to higher energy consumption and heat generation as a byproduct, thereby exacerbating the problem.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Alternatives are currently being explored by governments and researchers, such as more energy-efficient systems, passive cooling techniques, and the development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] However, balancing the demand for cooling with the need to reduce carbon footprints remains a complex and pressing issue.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] As renewable energy becomes cheaper and more popular, the energy source of air conditioners is shifting towards more renewable energy sources.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The danger of high-GWP refrigerants, such as HFCs, escaping into the atmosphere and trapping heat can be mitigated through development of low-GWP refrigerants.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Socioeconomic groups with a household income below around $10,000 (circa 2021) tend to have a low air conditioning adoption, which worsens heat-related mortality.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The lack of cooling can be hazardous, as areas with lower use of air conditioning correlate with higher rates of heat-related mortality and hospitalizations.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Premature mortality in New York City is projected to grow between 47% and 95% in 30 years, with lower-income and vulnerable populations most at risk.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Studies on the correlation between heat-related mortality and hospitalizations and living in low socioeconomic locations can be traced in Phoenix, Arizona, Hong Kong, China, Japan, and Italy.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Additionally, costs concerning health care can act as another barrier, as the lack of private health insurance during a 2009 heat wave in Australia, was associated with heat-related hospitalization.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A study examining the US cities of Chicago, Detroit, Minneapolis, and Pittsburgh found that black households were half as likely to have central air conditioning units when compared to their white counterparts.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Especially in cities, redlining and other historical practices mean that racial disparities are also played out in heat islands, increasing temperatures in certain parts of the city.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This is due to heat-absorbing building materials and pavements and lack of vegetation and shade coverage.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There have been initiatives that provide cooling solutions to low-income communities, such as public cooling spaces.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Cooling has allowed for growth of indoor home space and encouraged people, including children, to stay indoors more often.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It has also created uniformity of different geographical areas and climate zones.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Alternatives to continual air conditioning include passive cooling, passive solar cooling, natural ventilation, operating shades to reduce solar gain, using trees, architectural shades, windows (and using window coatings) to reduce solar gain.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Buildings designed with passive air conditioning are generally less expensive to construct and maintain than buildings with conventional HVAC systems with lower energy demands.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] While tens of air changes per hour, and cooling of tens of degrees, can be achieved with passive methods, site-specific microclimate must be taken into account, complicating building design.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Many techniques can be used to increase comfort and reduce the temperature in buildings.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] These include evaporative cooling, selective shading, wind, thermal convection, and heat storage.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Passive ventilation is the process of supplying air to and removing air from an indoor space without using mechanical systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] It refers to the flow of external air to an indoor space as a result of pressure differences arising from natural forces.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There are two types of natural ventilation occurring in buildings: *wind driven ventilation* and *buoyancy-driven ventilation*.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Wind driven ventilation arises from the different pressures created by wind around a building or structure, and openings being formed on the perimeter which then permit flow through the building.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Buoyancy-driven ventilation occurs as a result of the directional buoyancy force that results from temperature differences between the interior and exterior.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Since the internal heat gains which create temperature differences between the interior and exterior are created by natural processes, including the heat from people, and wind effects are variable, naturally ventilated buildings are sometimes called "breathing buildings".
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Natural solutions do not require energy for cooling purposes, and are therefore a very attractive solution.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Many ways to achieve this have been explored.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The structure of a building can help dissipate heat.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] For example, in Zimbabwe, Eastgate Development cut its energy use by 90% by utilizing termite mound inspired structures.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Coverage of windows can help reduce internal heat gain from sunlight.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Department of Energy estimates that window awnings can lower internal heat gain from sunlight by up to 77%.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The coating of roofs have also seen great success.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In the United States, painting roofs white has been shown to lower roof temperatures by as much as 30 °C.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Meanwhile, in China, a project involving the installation of green roofs — roofs covered with vegetation — not only reduced the cooling demands of buildings, but also lowered the average land surface temperature in the area by 0.91 °C.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Planting trees can also help mitigate the heat island effect.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] A study in Europe discovered that tree cover can reduce land surface temperatures in cities by as much as 12 °C during the summer.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In the United States, another study found that when tree cover reaches 40%, ground-level temperatures were lowered by nearly 6 °C.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is a building design approach that focuses on heat gain control and heat dissipation in a building in order to improve the indoor thermal comfort with low or no energy consumption.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This approach works either by preventing heat from entering the interior (heat gain prevention) or by removing heat from the building (natural cooling).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Natural cooling utilizes on-site energy, available from the natural environment, combined with the architectural design of building components (e.g. building envelope), rather than mechanical systems to dissipate heat.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Therefore, natural cooling depends not only on the architectural design of the building but on how the site's natural resources are used as heat sinks (i.e. everything that absorbs or dissipates heat).
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Examples of on-site heat sinks are the upper atmosphere (night sky), the outdoor air (wind), and the earth/soil.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Passive cooling is an important tool for design of buildings for climate change adaptation – reducing dependency on energy-intensive air conditioning in warming environments.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Passive daytime radiative cooling (PDRC) surfaces reflect incoming solar radiation and heat back into outer space through the infrared window for cooling during the daytime.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Daytime radiative cooling became possible with the ability to suppress solar heating using photonic structures, which emerged through a study by Raman et al.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] PDRCs can come in a variety of forms, including paint coatings and films, that are designed to be high in solar reflectance and thermal emittance.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] PDRC applications on building roofs and envelopes have demonstrated significant decreases in energy consumption and costs.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In suburban single-family residential areas, PDRC application on roofs can potentially lower energy costs by 26% to 46%.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] PDRCs are predicted to show a market size of ~$27 billion for indoor space cooling by 2025 and have undergone a surge in research and development since the 2010s.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Hand fans have existed since prehistory.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Large human-powered fans built into buildings include the punkah.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The 2nd-century Chinese inventor Ding Huan of the Han dynasty invented a rotary fan for air conditioning, with seven wheels 3 m (10 ft) in diameter and manually powered by prisoners.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] 712–762) of the Tang dynasty (618–907) had the Cool Hall (*Liang Dian* 涼殿) built in the imperial palace, which the *Tang Yulin* describes as having water-powered fan wheels for air conditioning as well as rising jet streams of water from fountains.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] During the subsequent Song dynasty (960–1279), written sources mentioned the air conditioning rotary fan as even more widely used.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In areas that are cold at night or in winter, heat storage is used.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Heat may be stored in earth or masonry; air is drawn past the masonry to heat or cool it.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In areas that are below freezing at night in winter, snow and ice can be collected and stored in ice houses for later use in cooling.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This technique is over 3,700 years old in the Middle East.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Harvesting outdoor ice during winter and transporting and storing for use in summer was practiced by wealthy Europeans in the early 1600s, and became popular in Europe and the Americas towards the end of the 1600s.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] This practice was replaced by mechanical compression-cycle icemakers.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] In dry, hot climates, the evaporative cooling effect may be used by placing water at the air intake, such that the draft draws air over water and then into the house.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] For this reason, it is sometimes said that the fountain, in the architecture of hot, arid climates, is like the fireplace in the architecture of cold climates.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Evaporative cooling also makes the air more humid, which can be beneficial in a dry desert climate.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] Evaporative coolers tend to feel as if they are not working during times of high humidity, when there is not much dry air with which the coolers can work to make the air as cool as possible for dwelling occupants.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] There is a longstanding political controversy about air conditioning, particularly in the nations of Europe, where the technology is relatively unadopted.
[src:consumer-electronics/air-conditioning] The strongest opposition generally originates from environmentalists, European federalists, and left-wing parties, while supporters tend to be from the political right.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] ash was first released via a posting to the comp.sources.unix Usenet news group, approved and moderated by Rich Salz on 30 May 1989.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] It was described as "a reimplementation of the System V shell [with] most features of that shell, plus some additions".
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Fast, small, and virtually compatible with the POSIX standard's specification of the Unix shell, ash did not provide line editing or command history mechanisms, because Almquist felt that such functionality should be moved into the terminal driver.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Myriad forks have been produced from the original ash release.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] These derivatives of ash are installed as the default shell (`/bin/sh`) on FreeBSD, NetBSD, DragonFly BSD, MINIX, and in some Linux distributions.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] MINIX 3.2 used the original ash version, whose test feature differed from POSIX.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] That version of the shell was replaced in MINIX 3.3.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Android used ash until Android 4.0, at which point it switched to mksh.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Chimera Linux uses FreeBSD's version of the ash as its default, which is quite unique in the Linux realm.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] In 1997 Herbert Xu ported `ash` from NetBSD to Debian Linux.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] In September 2002, with release 0.4.1, this port was renamed to **Dash** (**Debian Almquist shell**).
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Xu's main priorities are POSIX conformance and slim implementation.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Like its predecessor, Dash implements support for neither internationalization and localization nor multi-byte character encoding (both required in POSIX).
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Line editing and history support based on GNU Readline is optional (`--with-libedit`).
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Because of its slimness, Ubuntu decided to adopt Dash as the default `/bin/sh` in October 2006 with version 6.10.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] The reason for using Dash is faster shell script execution, especially during startup of the operating system, compared to previous versions of Debian and Ubuntu that used Bash for this purpose, although Bash is still the default login shell for interactive use.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] A result of the shift is that many shell scripts were found making use of Bash-specific functionalities ("bashisms") without properly declaring it in the shebang line.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] The problem was first spotted in Ubuntu and the maintainers decided to make all the scripts comply with the POSIX standard.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] The changes were later upstreamed to Debian, which eventually adopted Dash as its default `/bin/sh` too in Debian 6 (Squeeze), released in February 2011.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] As a result, Debian policy was amended to allow script developers to assume a largely POSIX-compliant shell, save for the extensions merged into Dash for convenience (`local`, `echo -n`, `test -a / -o`).
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] A similar transition has happened in Slackware Linux, although its version of `ash` is only partially based on Dash.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Ash (mainly the Dash fork) is also fairly popular in embedded Linux systems.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Dash version 0.3.8-5 was incorporated into BusyBox, the catch-all executable often employed in this area.
[src:consumer-electronics/almquist-shell] Modern BusyBox versions support additional Bash features which are enabled in modern distributions like Alpine Linux, Tiny Core Linux and Linux-based router firmware such as OpenWrt, Tomato and DD-WRT.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Radio broadcasting in the early 20th century brought the first major consumer product, the broadcast receiver.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Later products included telephones, televisions, calculators, cameras, video game consoles, mobile phones, personal computers, and MP3 players.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In the 2010s, consumer electronics stores often sold GPS, automotive electronics (vehicle audio), video game consoles, electronic musical instruments such as synthesizer keyboards, karaoke machines, digital cameras, and video players.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Such video playing equipment included VCRs in the 1980s and 1990s, and eventually DVD players and Blu-ray players.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Stores also sold smart light fixtures, network devices, camcorders, and smartphones.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some of the modern products being sold include virtual reality goggles, smart home devices that connect to the Internet, streaming devices, and wearable technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In the 2010s, most consumer electronics were based on digital technologies and increasingly merged with the computer and video game industry, in a trend often referred to as the consumerization of information technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics stores also began selling office and baby furniture.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics stores may be physical "brick and mortar" retail stores, online stores, or combinations of both.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Annual consumer electronics sales were expected to reach $2.9 trillion by 2020.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The sector is part of the electronics industry, which is, in turn, driven by the semiconductor industry.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] For its first fifty years, the phonograph turntable did not use electronics; the needle and sound horn were purely mechanical technologies.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] However, in the 1920s, radio broadcasting became the basis of the mass production of radio receivers.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The vacuum tubes that had made radios practical were used with record players as well.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This was to amplify the sound so that it could be played through a loudspeaker.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Television was invented soon after, but remained insignificant in the consumer market until the 1950s.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The first working transistor, a point-contact transistor, was invented by John Bardeen and Walter Houser Brattain at Bell Labs in 1947, which led to significant research in the field of solid-state semiconductors in the early-1950s.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The invention and development of the earliest transistors at Bell led to transistor radios, in turn promoting the emergence of the home entertainment consumer electronics industry starting in the 1950s.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This was largely due to the efforts of Tokyo Tsushin Kogyo (now Sony) in successfully commercializing transistor technology for a mass market, with affordable transistor radios and then transistorized television sets.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Integrated circuits (ICs) followed when manufacturers built circuits (usually for military purposes) on a single substrate using electrical connections between circuits within the chip itself.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] IC technology led to more advanced and cheaper consumer electronics, such as transistorized televisions, pocket calculators, and by the 1980s, video game consoles and personal computers affordable for regular middle-class families.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Beginning in the 1980s and continuing through the early 2000s, many consumer electronics, such as televisions and stereo systems, underwent digitization.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The introduction of compact discs (CDs) and personal computers during this period signalled a broader shift as digital computer technology and digital signals were increasingly integrated into consumer devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This transformation significantly altered their functionality and led to improved performance, such as enhanced image quality in televisions.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] These advancements were largely driven by Moore’s Law, which enabled rapid increases in processing power and reductions in cost and size.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In 2004, the consumer electronics industry was worth US $240 billion annually worldwide, comprising visual equipment, audio equipment, and games consoles.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The industry became global, with Asia Pacific having a 35% market share, Europe having 31.5%, the US having 23%, and the rest of the world owning the remainder.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Major players in this industry are household names like Sony, Samsung, Philips, Sanyo, and Sharp.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The increase in popularity of such domestic appliances as 'white goods' is a characteristic element of consumption patterns during the golden age of the Western economy.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Europe's White Goods industry has evolved over the past 40 years, first by changing tariff barriers, and later by technical and demand shifts.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The spending on domestic appliances has claimed only a tiny fraction of disposable income, rising from 0.5 percent in the US in 1920 to about 2 percent in 1980.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Yet, the sequence of electrical and mechanical durables have altered the activities and experiences of households in America and Britain in the twentieth century.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] With the expansion of cookers, vacuum cleaners, refrigerators, washing machines, radios, televisions, air conditioning, and microwave ovens, households have gained an escalating number of appliances.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Despite the ubiquity of these goods, their diffusion is not well understood.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some types of appliances diffuse more frequently than others.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics products such as the digital distribution of video games have become increasingly based on the internet and digital technologies.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry has primarily merged with the software industry in what is increasingly referred to as the consumerization of information technology.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] One overriding characteristic of consumer electronic products is the trend of ever-falling prices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This is driven by gains in manufacturing efficiency and automation, lower labor costs as manufacturing has moved to lower-wage countries, and improvements in semiconductor design.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Semiconductor components benefit from Moore's law, an observed principle which states that, for a given price, semiconductor functionality doubles every two years.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Although consumer electronics shows a trend towards convergence, consumers still face varied purchasing decisions.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Product information therefore needs to remain current and comparable for the consumer to support informed choices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Factors such as style, price, specification, and performance all play a role in these decisions.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] At the same time, there is a gradual shift towards e-commerce web-storefronts.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Many products include Internet access using technologies such as Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, EDGE, or Ethernet.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Products not traditionally associated with computer use (such as TVs or Hi-fi equipment) now provide options to connect to the Internet or to a computer using a home network to provide access to digital content.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The desire for high-definition (HD) content has led the industry to develop a number of technologies, such as WirelessHD or ITU-T G.hn, which are optimized for distribution of HD content between consumer electronic devices in a home.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry faces consumers with unpredictable tastes on the demand side, supplier-related delays or disruptions on the supply side, and production challenges occurring in the process.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The high rate of technology evolution or revolution requires large investments without any guarantee of profitable returns.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] As a result, the big players rely on global markets to achieve economies of scale.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Even these companies sometimes have to cooperate with each other, for instance on standards, to reduce the risk of their investments.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In supply chain management, there is much discussion on risks related to such aspects of supply chains as short product lifecycles, high competition combined with cooperation, and globalization.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The consumer electronics industry is the very embodiment of these aspects of supply chain management and related risks.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] While some of the supply and demand related risks are similar to such industries as the toy industry, the consumer electronics industry faces additional risks due to its vertically integrated supply chains.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] There are also numerous supply-chain-wide contextual risks that cut across the supply chain especially impacting companies with global supply chains.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] These include cultural differences in multinational operations, environmental risk, regulations risk, and exchange rate risk across multiple countries.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Whether or not demand is comparable across countries affects the extent of the gains from international integration.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In addition, consumer preferences change over time to disturb existing patterns of behavior.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A feature of some industries is that demand for variety increases as the market moves from first-time buying to replacement demand.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A resource to further understand this idea of consumer preferences can be observed through Lizabeth Cohen's book titled, "A Consumers' Republic", "Only if we have large demands can we expect large production".
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The electronics industry, especially consumer electronics, emerged in the 20th century and has become a global industry worth billions of dollars.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Contemporary society uses all manner of electronic devices built-in automated or semi-automated factories operated by the industry.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Most consumer electronics are manufactured in China, due to maintenance cost, availability of materials, quality, and speed as opposed to other countries such as the United States.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Cities such as Shenzhen and Dongguan have become important production centers for the industry, attracting many consumer electronics companies such as Apple Inc.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] An electronic component is any essential discrete device or physical entity in an electronic system used to affect electrons or their associated fields.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronic components are mostly industrial products, available in a singular form, and are not to be confused with electrical elements, conceptual abstractions representing idealized electronic components.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronics such as personal computers use various types of software.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Embedded software is used within some consumer electronics, such as mobile phones.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This type of software may be embedded within the hardware of electronic devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics include software that is used on a personal computer in conjunction with electronic devices, such as camcorders and digital cameras, and third-party software for such devices also exists.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics adhere to protocols, such as connection protocols "to high speed bi-directional signals".
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In telecommunications, a communications protocol is a system of digital rules for data exchange within or between computers.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The Consumer Electronics Show (CES) trade show has taken place yearly in Las Vegas, Nevada since its foundation in 1973.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The event, which grew from having 100 exhibitors in its inaugural year to more than 4,500 exhibiting companies in its 2020 edition, features the latest in consumer electronics, speeches by industry experts and innovation awards.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The IFA Berlin trade show has taken place in Berlin, Germany since its foundation in 1924.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The event features new consumer electronics and speeches by industry pioneers.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the world's largest professional society, has many initiatives to advance the state of the art of consumer electronics.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] IEEE has a dedicated society of thousands of professionals to promote CE, called the Consumer Electronics Society (CESoc).
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] IEEE has multiple periodicals and international conferences to promote CE and encourage collaborative research and development in CE.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The flagship conference of CESoc, called IEEE International Conference on Consumer Electronics (ICCE), is in its 35th year.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) Computer Society also have initiated a conference to research on next generation consumer electronics as Smart Electronics.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The conference, named IEEE Symposium on Smart Electronics Systems (IEEE-iSES) is on its 9th year.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronics retailing is a significant part of the retail industry in many countries.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Broad-based retailers, such as Walmart and Target, also sell consumer electronics in many of their stores.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In April 2014, retail e-commerce sales were the highest in the consumer electronic and computer categories as well.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Some consumer electronics retailers offer extended warranties on products with programs such as *SquareTrade*.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] An electronics district is an area of commerce with a high density of retail stores that sell consumer electronics.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Consumer electronic service can refer to the maintenance of said products.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] When consumer electronics have malfunctions, they may sometimes be repaired.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In 2013, in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, the increased popularity in listening to sound from analog audio devices, such as phonographs, as opposed to digital sound, has sparked a noticeable increase of business for the electronic repair industry there.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A mobile phone, cellular phone, cell phone, cellphone, handphone, or hand phone, sometimes shortened to simply mobile, cell or just phone, is a portable telephone that can make and receive calls over a radio frequency link while the user is moving within a telephone service area.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The radio frequency link establishes a connection to the switching systems of a mobile phone operator, which provides access to the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Modern mobile telephone services use a cellular network architecture and, therefore, mobile telephones are called *cellular telephones* or *cell phones* in North America.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In addition to telephony, digital mobile phones (2G) support a variety of other services, such as text messaging, MMS, email, Internet access, short-range wireless communications (infrared, Bluetooth), business applications, video games and digital photography.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Mobile phones offering only those capabilities are known as feature phones; mobile phones which offer greatly advanced computing capabilities are referred to as smartphones.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A smartphone is a portable device that combines mobile telephone and computing functions into one unit.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] In 2017, Greenpeace USA published a study of 17 of the world's leading consumer electronics companies about their energy and resource consumption and the use of chemicals.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronic devices use thousands of rare metals and rare earth elements (40 on average for a smartphone), these materials are extracted and refined using water and energy-intensive processes.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] These metals are also used in the renewable energy industry meaning that consumer electronics are directly competing for the raw materials.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The energy consumption of consumer electronics and their environmental impact, either from their production processes or the disposal of the devices, is increasing steadily.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] EIA estimates that electronic devices and gadgets account for about 10%–15% of the energy use in American homes – largely because of their number; the average house has dozens of electronic devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The energy consumption of consumer electronics increases – in America and Europe – to about 50% of household consumption if the term is redefined to include home appliances such as refrigerators, dryers, clothes washers and dishwashers.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Standby power – used by consumer electronics and appliances while they are turned off – accounts for 5–10% of total household energy consumption, costing $100 annually to the average household in the United States.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A study by United States Department of Energy's Berkeley Lab found that videocassette recorders (VCRs) consume more electricity during the course of a year in standby mode than when they are used to record or playback videos.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Similar findings were obtained concerning satellite boxes, which consume almost the same amount of energy in "on" and "off" modes.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A 2012 study in the United Kingdom, carried out by the Energy Saving Trust, found that the devices using the most power on standby mode included televisions, satellite boxes, and other video and audio equipment.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The study concluded that UK households could save up to £86 per year by switching devices off instead of using standby mode.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A report from the International Energy Agency in 2014 found that $80 billion of power is wasted globally per year due to inefficiency of electronic devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Consumers can reduce unwanted use of standby power by unplugging their devices, using power strips with switches, or by buying devices that are standardized for better energy management, particularly Energy Star-marked products.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] A high number of different metals and low concentration rates in electronics means that recycling is limited and energy intensive.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronic waste describes discarded electrical or electronic devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Many consumer electronics may contain toxic minerals and elements, and many electronic scrap components, such as CRTs, may contain contaminants such as lead, cadmium, beryllium, mercury, dioxins, or brominated flame retardants.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronic waste recycling may involve significant risk to workers and communities and great care must be taken to avoid unsafe exposure in recycling operations and leaking of materials such as heavy metals from landfills and incinerator ashes.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] However, large amounts of the produced electronic waste from developed countries is exported, and handled by the informal sector in countries like India, despite the fact that exporting electronic waste to them is illegal.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Strong informal sector can be a problem for the safe and clean recycling.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] E-waste policies have evolved since the 1970s, with priorities shifting over time.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Initially, the focus was on safer disposal methods due to the toxic materials often found in electronic waste.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Over the years, attention turned to the recovery of valuable metals and plastics that could be recycled.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] More recently, the emphasis has shifted once again, this time toward reusing entire devices.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] New guidelines promoting 'preparation for reuse' highlight the growing importance of repair and reuse, signaling a gradual change in public and policy attitudes.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] With turnover of small household appliances high and costs relatively low, many consumers will throw unwanted electrical goods in the normal dustbin, meaning that items of potentially high reuse or recycling value go to landfills.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] While more oversized items such as washing machines are usually collected, it has been estimated that the 160,000 tonnes of EEE in regular waste collections were worth £220 million.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] 23% of EEE (Electrical and electronic equipment) taken to Household Waste Recycling Centres was immediately resalable – or would be with minor repairs or refurbishment.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] This indicates a lack of awareness among consumers about where and how to dispose of EEE and the potential value of things that are going in the bin.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] For the reuse and repair of electrical goods to increase substantially in the UK, some barriers must be overcome.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] These include people's mistrust of used equipment in terms of whether it will be functional, safe and the stigma for some of owning second-hand goods.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] But the benefits of reuse could allow lower-income households access to previously unaffordable technology while helping the environment at the same time.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Desktop monitors and laptops can contribute to major physical health concerns known as repetitive strain injuries.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] For example, when users are forced to bend to see electronic screens better, they may experience chronic neck and back pains.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] The best-known disease in this category is carpal tunnel syndrome.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Other conditions include de Quervain syndrome, a condition that affects tendons in the thumb.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Electronic use before bed is also associated with poorer sleep quality and sleep duration.
[src:consumer-electronics/consumer-electronics] Poor quality, shorter sleep is associated with various health conditions such as obesity and diabetes.
